1
00:00:31,958 --> 00:00:33,791
♪

2
00:00:34,458 --> 00:00:38,333
My name is Shirosuke Inudou.
Warden of Abashiri Prison.

3
00:00:38,416 --> 00:00:40,041
Nice to meet you.

4
00:00:40,125 --> 00:00:42,166
Inudou.

5
00:00:42,250 --> 00:00:44,208
[gasps]

6
00:00:44,291 --> 00:00:46,541
Uh, who might your friend be?

7
00:00:46,625 --> 00:00:48,541
[SUZUKAWA]
Sugimoto, my guard.

8
00:00:48,625 --> 00:00:51,125
Five years ago,
a brutal criminal

9
00:00:51,208 --> 00:00:55,125
unfortunately bit off his face
in a savage attack.

10
00:00:55,208 --> 00:00:57,000
He may look
a little bit different,

11
00:00:57,083 --> 00:00:59,416
but he's still
very good at his job.

12
00:00:59,500 --> 00:01:01,833
Inudou!

13
00:01:01,916 --> 00:01:04,291
Uh... I'm sorry to hear that.

14
00:01:05,375 --> 00:01:08,041
I can't believe
that actually worked.

15
00:01:08,125 --> 00:01:11,833
I was told Yoshitake Shiraishi
was being held here.

16
00:01:11,916 --> 00:01:14,833
I've come because I want him
sent back to Abashiri.

17
00:01:14,916 --> 00:01:16,541
Shiraishi?

18
00:01:16,625 --> 00:01:19,583
I'm not aware of a prisoner
by that name here.

19
00:01:19,666 --> 00:01:21,041
[YODOGAWA]
Where did he find out?

20
00:01:21,125 --> 00:01:22,291
Who the hell told him?

21
00:01:22,375 --> 00:01:24,333
Do you dare to lie to my face?!

22
00:01:24,416 --> 00:01:26,250
[SUGIMOTO moaning]

23
00:01:26,333 --> 00:01:28,416
Inudou.

24
00:01:28,500 --> 00:01:29,791
[sighs]

25
00:01:29,875 --> 00:01:31,708
[SUZUKAWA clears throat]

26
00:01:31,791 --> 00:01:34,916
Not only did you dare
to illegally transport prisoners

27
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:37,000
from Abashiri
during my absence,

28
00:01:37,083 --> 00:01:39,875
you then quite stupidly
allowed all of them to escape.

29
00:01:39,958 --> 00:01:43,000
You've made an incredible mess.
Now I'm here.

30
00:01:43,083 --> 00:01:45,041
I came to here to clean up
the idiotic muddle

31
00:01:45,125 --> 00:01:46,666
the Seventh has created.

32
00:01:46,750 --> 00:01:48,000
Regiment Commander.

33
00:01:48,083 --> 00:01:49,416
[gasping]

34
00:01:54,083 --> 00:01:56,666
Contact Lieutenant Tsurumi
in Otaru, now.

35
00:01:56,750 --> 00:01:58,000
♪

36
00:02:03,958 --> 00:02:05,958
So, there's a man
calling himself

37
00:02:06,041 --> 00:02:08,708
Shirosuke Inudou
in Asahikawa, huh?

38
00:02:10,333 --> 00:02:11,333
[chuckles]

39
00:03:42,833 --> 00:03:44,125
[YODOGAWA gasps]

40
00:03:44,208 --> 00:03:45,541
I don't understand.

41
00:03:46,625 --> 00:03:48,666
What are you planning
to do with this?

42
00:03:48,750 --> 00:03:52,000
Do you think I'll accept a bribe
for Yoshitake Shiraishi?

43
00:03:52,083 --> 00:03:53,541
[SUZUKAWA]
That's not what this is.

44
00:03:53,625 --> 00:03:55,333
-The bills are fake.
-Huh?

45
00:03:56,583 --> 00:03:59,458
Look at this. It's the plate
used to make them.

46
00:03:59,541 --> 00:04:02,666
We confiscated it from a genius
counterfeiter whom we arrested.

47
00:04:02,750 --> 00:04:04,125
Look at that work.

48
00:04:04,208 --> 00:04:06,750
Do you know anything
about the Continental dollar

49
00:04:06,833 --> 00:04:08,833
during the American Revolution?

50
00:04:08,916 --> 00:04:11,000
Or Napoleon's
counterfeit gulden?

51
00:04:11,083 --> 00:04:13,500
Spreading counterfeit currency
in a time of war

52
00:04:13,583 --> 00:04:15,000
to cause economic chaos

53
00:04:15,083 --> 00:04:17,750
is an extremely
effective measure.

54
00:04:17,833 --> 00:04:19,666
I have no doubt
this man would be able

55
00:04:19,750 --> 00:04:23,333
to make an accurate copy
of any nation's currency.

56
00:04:23,416 --> 00:04:25,958
I happen to think he could be
quite a valuable asset

57
00:04:26,041 --> 00:04:28,041
to the Japanese Army
in the future.

58
00:04:29,083 --> 00:04:32,208
What do you say? You interested?

59
00:04:32,291 --> 00:04:34,041
[groans quietly]

60
00:04:34,125 --> 00:04:35,583
[SUGIMOTO scoffs]

61
00:04:35,666 --> 00:04:38,666
I thought this guy was just
some washed-up fraudster.

62
00:04:38,750 --> 00:04:42,083
Now I see why Hijikata kept him
as a secret weapon.

63
00:04:42,166 --> 00:04:45,541
Kiyohiro Suzukawa's
no ordinary con artist.

64
00:04:45,625 --> 00:04:46,833
Just one more push

65
00:04:46,916 --> 00:04:49,166
and the Lieutenant Colonel
will give in.

66
00:04:51,250 --> 00:04:52,583
I'm proposing a trade,

67
00:04:52,666 --> 00:04:54,458
the counterfeiter
for Shiraishi.

68
00:04:55,916 --> 00:04:58,541
Lieutenant Colonel Yodogawa.

69
00:04:58,625 --> 00:05:01,750
I can't help noticing that
since the Russo-Japanese War,

70
00:05:01,833 --> 00:05:05,291
every other lieutenant colonel
is made full colonel.

71
00:05:05,375 --> 00:05:06,958
Except for you.

72
00:05:07,041 --> 00:05:09,666
Which seems like
such a terrible injustice.

73
00:05:09,750 --> 00:05:12,083
Don't you believe
you're being treated unfairly?

74
00:05:12,166 --> 00:05:13,333
[gasps]

75
00:05:15,541 --> 00:05:16,666
[SUZUKAWA]
Listen to me.

76
00:05:16,750 --> 00:05:18,916
This will be your path
to promotion.

77
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:20,583
[gasping]

78
00:05:22,458 --> 00:05:23,833
[OPERATOR]
You've reached the switchboard.

79
00:05:23,916 --> 00:05:25,333
Local or long distance, please?

80
00:05:25,416 --> 00:05:26,666
[TSURUMI over phone]
Long-distance!

81
00:05:26,750 --> 00:05:28,416
Get me the Seventh Division
in Asahikawa.

82
00:05:28,500 --> 00:05:29,916
Regiment 27!

83
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:32,375
It's me.

84
00:05:32,458 --> 00:05:35,083
Do not go along with
Lieutenant Colonel Yodogawa.

85
00:05:35,166 --> 00:05:37,791
Don't let anyone
see Shiraishi, understand?

86
00:05:37,875 --> 00:05:41,125
Believe me, if Inudou were to
take one step out of Abashiri,

87
00:05:41,208 --> 00:05:42,625
I would obviously
know about it

88
00:05:42,708 --> 00:05:44,166
because my men there
would tell me...

89
00:05:44,250 --> 00:05:45,833
You're too close
to the receiver, sir.

90
00:05:45,916 --> 00:05:48,625
[TSURUMI]
Send Second Lieutenant Koito!

91
00:05:48,708 --> 00:05:51,916
Oh, hell.
That can't be a good thing.

92
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:53,416
That's one of
Lieutenant Tsurumi's

93
00:05:53,500 --> 00:05:55,250
favorite Satsuma messengers.

94
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:01,041
Huh?

95
00:06:02,708 --> 00:06:06,125
What is this?
What's going on?

96
00:06:06,208 --> 00:06:08,125
[SUZUKAWA] I have one of my men
waiting out front

97
00:06:08,208 --> 00:06:09,416
with the counterfeiter.

98
00:06:10,416 --> 00:06:13,208
Let's do the exchange outside.

99
00:06:13,291 --> 00:06:14,750
I'm sure you can understand

100
00:06:14,833 --> 00:06:16,666
how we might have
a few trust issues

101
00:06:16,750 --> 00:06:19,125
after the incident
at Abashiri.

102
00:06:19,208 --> 00:06:20,458
[SHIRAISHI]
Oh, my God.

103
00:06:20,541 --> 00:06:22,583
The likeness is pretty uncanny,

104
00:06:22,666 --> 00:06:24,458
but this guy
isn't really Inudou.

105
00:06:24,541 --> 00:06:27,791
Based on the height and build
and the way his clothes hang,

106
00:06:27,875 --> 00:06:30,125
I'd say the weirdo is Sugimoto.

107
00:06:30,208 --> 00:06:32,500
They really came here
to get me back?

108
00:06:32,583 --> 00:06:34,500
-[door opens]
-[gasps]

109
00:06:34,583 --> 00:06:36,291
♪

110
00:06:38,250 --> 00:06:40,166
What is it,
Lieutenant Koito?

111
00:06:40,250 --> 00:06:43,250
I've come with a message
from Lieutenant Tsurumi.

112
00:06:43,333 --> 00:06:45,875
He demands that no one
make contact with Shiraishi

113
00:06:45,958 --> 00:06:48,750
until he himself arrives.

114
00:06:48,833 --> 00:06:52,000
[SUGIMOTO]
Not good. He works for Tsurumi?

115
00:06:52,083 --> 00:06:55,833
And are you under any obligation
to obey the lieutenant's orders?

116
00:06:55,916 --> 00:06:57,125
Lieutenant Colonel?

117
00:06:57,208 --> 00:06:58,458
[moaning]

118
00:06:58,541 --> 00:06:59,916
Get out.

119
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:02,041
You have no business here.

120
00:07:02,125 --> 00:07:03,250
[KOITO]
Inudou.

121
00:07:04,708 --> 00:07:06,875
[speaking in Satsuma dialect]

122
00:07:06,958 --> 00:07:08,541
Chinchin what?

123
00:07:08,625 --> 00:07:10,875
-[SUZUKAWA grunts]
-[SUGIMOTO moaning]

124
00:07:10,958 --> 00:07:13,375
Forgive me. I've heard it said
that during his time

125
00:07:13,458 --> 00:07:16,041
as the warden of Kabato Prison
in Tsukigata,

126
00:07:16,125 --> 00:07:19,416
Inudou spent a lot of time
with prisoners from Satsuma.

127
00:07:19,500 --> 00:07:21,333
I was led to believe
that he's able to speak

128
00:07:21,416 --> 00:07:23,208
the Satsuma dialect very well.

129
00:07:23,291 --> 00:07:25,625
Koito, what the hell
are you doing?

130
00:07:25,708 --> 00:07:27,916
[speaking in Satsuma dialect]

131
00:07:29,500 --> 00:07:30,833
[grunts]

132
00:07:35,291 --> 00:07:37,666
[speaking in Satsuma dialect]

133
00:07:37,750 --> 00:07:38,708
[gasps]

134
00:07:38,791 --> 00:07:40,083
[sighs]

135
00:07:40,166 --> 00:07:42,166
[speaking in Satsuma dialect]

136
00:07:42,250 --> 00:07:44,708
[speaking in Satsuma dialect]

137
00:07:45,708 --> 00:07:48,458
[SUGIMOTO]
Okay, yeah, he's a genius.

138
00:07:48,541 --> 00:07:51,000
I can't believe
he mastered that so quickly.

139
00:07:51,083 --> 00:07:53,625
[speaking in Satsuma dialect]

140
00:07:53,708 --> 00:07:56,041
[speaking in Satsuma dialect]

141
00:07:56,125 --> 00:07:57,333
[clears throat]

142
00:07:57,416 --> 00:08:00,083
[speaking in Satsuma dialect]

143
00:08:01,333 --> 00:08:04,791
[speaking in Satsuma dialect]

144
00:08:04,875 --> 00:08:05,958
[SHIRAISHI]
This is nuts.

145
00:08:06,041 --> 00:08:07,750
What are they saying
to each other?

146
00:08:07,833 --> 00:08:10,250
Are they really both
speaking Japanese?

147
00:08:10,333 --> 00:08:13,833
[speaking in Satsuma dialect]

148
00:08:13,916 --> 00:08:16,125
[speaking in Satsuma dialect]

149
00:08:18,416 --> 00:08:20,541
[groaning]

150
00:08:20,625 --> 00:08:22,666
[grunts]

151
00:08:22,750 --> 00:08:25,041
According to Lieutenant Tsurumi,

152
00:08:25,125 --> 00:08:28,000
Inudou couldn't drink, at all.

153
00:08:29,041 --> 00:08:30,416
[gasping]

154
00:08:31,791 --> 00:08:33,541
You bastards tried to fool me?!

155
00:08:34,916 --> 00:08:37,291
I should've thrown this idiot
right into the damn river.

156
00:08:37,375 --> 00:08:38,291
Please don't do that!

157
00:08:38,375 --> 00:08:40,333
You're not to hurt Shiraishi.

158
00:08:40,416 --> 00:08:42,875
Tsurumi will kill you.
And by you, I mean me.

159
00:08:42,958 --> 00:08:44,625
[grunts]

160
00:08:44,708 --> 00:08:45,958
Sugimoto!

161
00:08:46,041 --> 00:08:50,166
I'm still Immortal Sugimoto,
rat bastards!

162
00:08:50,250 --> 00:08:51,416
[yelling]

163
00:08:51,500 --> 00:08:52,958
-After them!
-Yes, sir!

164
00:08:53,041 --> 00:08:54,250
-[gunshot]
-[groans]

165
00:08:54,333 --> 00:08:55,750
They have men outside.

166
00:08:57,500 --> 00:09:00,041
-[grunting] Man, that smarts.
-This way, Shiraishi.

167
00:09:00,125 --> 00:09:02,125
Kiroranke and the others
have horses waiting.

168
00:09:02,208 --> 00:09:03,458
[panting]

169
00:09:03,541 --> 00:09:05,666
[SHIRAISHI]
Sugimoto, are you gonna be okay?

170
00:09:05,750 --> 00:09:07,125
[SUGIMOTO]
You have to run!

171
00:09:08,125 --> 00:09:09,416
Stop them!

172
00:09:11,500 --> 00:09:13,916
Sugimoto, this way's bad.

173
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:16,541
Run to the south. That way!

174
00:09:16,625 --> 00:09:19,000
Unluckily for us, those gunshots
frightened the bees

175
00:09:19,083 --> 00:09:20,541
right out of their hives.

176
00:09:20,625 --> 00:09:22,583
[panting]

177
00:09:22,666 --> 00:09:24,458
[gasps]

178
00:09:24,541 --> 00:09:26,208
Sugimoto was hit pretty badly!

179
00:09:26,291 --> 00:09:28,833
Good thing he's immortal.
You run or you die.

180
00:09:28,916 --> 00:09:31,250
Are you kidding? He's hurt.
He needs help.

181
00:09:31,333 --> 00:09:33,583
He can't just keep
running indefinitely.

182
00:09:33,666 --> 00:09:35,041
[SUGIMOTO]
Shiraishi.

183
00:09:35,125 --> 00:09:36,750
If I don't make it,

184
00:09:36,833 --> 00:09:38,375
then it's up to you
to get Asirpa

185
00:09:38,458 --> 00:09:40,416
to Abashiri Prison, understand?

186
00:09:40,500 --> 00:09:42,500
Uh... [sighs]

187
00:09:42,583 --> 00:09:44,041
♪

188
00:09:45,208 --> 00:09:47,000
[panting]

189
00:09:47,083 --> 00:09:48,041
[gasps]

190
00:09:49,500 --> 00:09:51,541
♪

191
00:09:53,041 --> 00:09:54,833
What the bloody hell is that?

192
00:09:54,916 --> 00:09:56,625
Prototype for a hot air balloon.

193
00:09:56,708 --> 00:09:57,708
Hmm. That's it.

194
00:09:57,791 --> 00:09:59,666
We're stealing that balloon.

195
00:09:59,750 --> 00:10:02,625
[clamoring]

196
00:10:02,708 --> 00:10:05,333
Everyone, get back.
Further back than that.

197
00:10:05,416 --> 00:10:07,291
[grunts]
Give it to me!

198
00:10:07,375 --> 00:10:09,250
Come on, I said hurry up.
Get it going.

199
00:10:09,333 --> 00:10:11,208
[SUGIMOTO]
Get back. We'll shoot!

200
00:10:11,291 --> 00:10:13,041
You can't shoot, you idiot!

201
00:10:13,125 --> 00:10:14,791
You might ignite the hydrogen.

202
00:10:14,875 --> 00:10:15,833
Get 'em down!

203
00:10:15,916 --> 00:10:18,500
[clamoring]

204
00:10:18,583 --> 00:10:20,958
Would you get the hell
off of it, damn you?

205
00:10:21,041 --> 00:10:23,250
♪

206
00:10:25,541 --> 00:10:27,833
Hey. Get back here
with my sword!

207
00:10:27,916 --> 00:10:29,333
[grunting]

208
00:10:34,250 --> 00:10:36,416
[gasping]

209
00:10:36,500 --> 00:10:37,458
[grunts]

210
00:10:42,500 --> 00:10:43,750
Hmm.

211
00:10:43,833 --> 00:10:45,791
Second Lieutenant.

212
00:10:47,875 --> 00:10:49,375
[HIJIKATA]
What is that thing?

213
00:10:50,833 --> 00:10:53,041
Sugimoto's group is on it.

214
00:10:53,125 --> 00:10:55,833
Those gunshots we heard
were from them after all.

215
00:10:55,916 --> 00:10:58,166
They're using it to escape!

216
00:10:58,250 --> 00:11:00,666
♪

217
00:11:04,458 --> 00:11:06,208
I'll handle it.

218
00:11:06,291 --> 00:11:07,541
Bayonet.

219
00:11:07,625 --> 00:11:10,250
He uses Satsuma swordsmanship.
Jigen style.

220
00:11:10,333 --> 00:11:13,708
There's no way you can fight him
with two bullets inside of you.

221
00:11:13,791 --> 00:11:15,000
[gasps]

222
00:11:15,083 --> 00:11:18,833
[KOITO]
Hyakunosuke Ogata. You traitor!

223
00:11:18,916 --> 00:11:21,250
[speaking in Satsuma dialect]

224
00:11:27,333 --> 00:11:29,000
Yeah, sorry, but as usual,

225
00:11:29,083 --> 00:11:30,833
I have no idea
what you're saying right now,

226
00:11:30,916 --> 00:11:32,458
Second Lieutenant Koito.

227
00:11:32,541 --> 00:11:34,458
Have you ever noticed
that when you get upset,

228
00:11:34,541 --> 00:11:35,916
you talk really fast?

229
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:37,750
[speaking in Satsuma dialect]

230
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:39,875
[grunts]

231
00:11:39,958 --> 00:11:41,333
Don't block it.

232
00:11:41,416 --> 00:11:43,458
[yelling]

233
00:11:46,333 --> 00:11:47,708
[screaming]

234
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:50,000
[gasps]

235
00:11:55,291 --> 00:11:56,875
What's he doing?

236
00:11:56,958 --> 00:11:58,333
[grunts]

237
00:11:58,416 --> 00:11:59,583
Shiraishi!

238
00:11:59,666 --> 00:12:02,083
♪

239
00:12:02,166 --> 00:12:04,625
[speaking in Satsuma dialect]

240
00:12:07,583 --> 00:12:09,125
[laughing]

241
00:12:09,208 --> 00:12:10,791
Bye-bye, crazy Koito.

242
00:12:10,875 --> 00:12:13,583
[SUGIMOTO] Shiraishi, you're
about to slam into the trees!

243
00:12:13,666 --> 00:12:14,583
[gasps]

244
00:12:14,666 --> 00:12:16,625
[groaning]

245
00:12:23,500 --> 00:12:25,041
Asirpa!

246
00:12:25,125 --> 00:12:27,291
♪

247
00:12:36,875 --> 00:12:38,791
[sighs]

248
00:12:38,875 --> 00:12:41,833
[speaking in Satsuma dialect]

249
00:12:51,416 --> 00:12:53,541
One of the bullets
passed through your shoulder,

250
00:12:53,625 --> 00:12:56,000
but the other one
is still in your left breast.

251
00:12:56,083 --> 00:12:57,583
We'll need to get
that out later.

252
00:12:57,666 --> 00:13:00,291
I can't believe you were willing
to take that kind of risk

253
00:13:00,375 --> 00:13:02,625
to get me back again.

254
00:13:02,708 --> 00:13:06,500
I mean, I'm the Escape King.
I could've gotten away myself.

255
00:13:06,583 --> 00:13:09,208
Everyone else was
going to give up on you.

256
00:13:09,291 --> 00:13:12,541
The one who insisted
that we didn't was Sugimoto.

257
00:13:12,625 --> 00:13:14,208
Ah!

258
00:13:14,291 --> 00:13:15,625
Is that true?

259
00:13:15,708 --> 00:13:18,250
[SUGIMOTO] You'll help us
when we get to Abashiri.

260
00:13:18,333 --> 00:13:21,541
I know you will.
I believe in you.

261
00:13:21,625 --> 00:13:24,333
That's why I decided
to save you.

262
00:13:24,416 --> 00:13:27,541
But I did remember something,
Shiraishi.

263
00:13:28,833 --> 00:13:32,291
That strange old man we met at
the herring fishery longhouse.

264
00:13:33,541 --> 00:13:34,625
[gasps]

265
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:37,916
Just admit it.

266
00:13:38,000 --> 00:13:39,708
You were working with Hijikata.

267
00:13:39,791 --> 00:13:41,041
[shuddering]

268
00:13:41,125 --> 00:13:42,625
♪

269
00:13:46,541 --> 00:13:48,208
[SUGIMOTO]
Wait. Don't run!

270
00:13:48,291 --> 00:13:49,458
Look at this.

271
00:13:51,666 --> 00:13:53,666
[gasps]
Isn't that...

272
00:13:53,750 --> 00:13:55,958
[SUGIMOTO] The copy of
Kazou Henmi's tattoos

273
00:13:56,041 --> 00:13:58,916
that you gave to Ushiyama
in Sapporo.

274
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:02,041
Toshizou Hijikata
showed it to me.

275
00:14:02,125 --> 00:14:03,708
I took a careful look...

276
00:14:06,125 --> 00:14:07,583
and it was a fake.

277
00:14:10,583 --> 00:14:13,625
The truth is,
Shiraishi never betrayed us.

278
00:14:14,916 --> 00:14:16,833
Yes, that's absolutely right!

279
00:14:16,916 --> 00:14:18,208
What did I tell you?

280
00:14:18,291 --> 00:14:20,833
I said I'll always
bet on you, my friend.

281
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:27,583
[sputtering]

282
00:14:27,666 --> 00:14:31,083
Hey. This thing's
acting really weird.

283
00:14:31,166 --> 00:14:33,791
-[SHIRAISHI grunting]
-[clanging]

284
00:14:33,875 --> 00:14:35,291
-[ASIRPA grunting]
-[clanging]

285
00:14:35,375 --> 00:14:37,083
[OGATA]
Would you stop it?

286
00:14:37,166 --> 00:14:39,166
[SHIRAISHI exclaiming]

287
00:14:39,250 --> 00:14:41,208
Guys, you might wanna
look at this!

288
00:14:42,166 --> 00:14:43,750
This is bad.

289
00:14:43,833 --> 00:14:45,541
Pawci casi.

290
00:14:45,625 --> 00:14:49,125
Quite simply, it means "village
where the Pawci-Kamuy live."

291
00:14:49,208 --> 00:14:52,125
It's believed to be the fortress
of the Pawci-Kamuy.

292
00:14:52,208 --> 00:14:55,958
The Pawci are sex demons,
and they're not very good gods.

293
00:14:56,041 --> 00:14:58,583
It's said anyone they possess
will strip off their clothes

294
00:14:58,666 --> 00:14:59,791
and start dancing.

295
00:14:59,875 --> 00:15:01,125
[laughing]

296
00:15:01,208 --> 00:15:02,958
That's so ridiculous!

297
00:15:03,041 --> 00:15:06,208
The Ainu have some
big imaginations, don't they?

298
00:15:10,208 --> 00:15:11,583
[SUGIMOTO]
We're about 40 kilometers away

299
00:15:11,666 --> 00:15:13,833
from the Seventh Division's
barracks.

300
00:15:13,916 --> 00:15:17,250
[OGATA] I saw soldiers on horses
following us from the air.

301
00:15:17,333 --> 00:15:19,041
That thing's not
exactly hard to spot.

302
00:15:19,125 --> 00:15:21,291
They should know
about where we are.

303
00:15:21,375 --> 00:15:23,625
If we don't hurry,
they'll catch up to us.

304
00:15:23,708 --> 00:15:26,583
First, we need
to treat Sugimoto.

305
00:15:26,666 --> 00:15:30,916
I found some retannoya,
or alpine yarrow.

306
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:32,333
Put the crushed leaves
on the wound

307
00:15:32,416 --> 00:15:33,666
and it stops the bleeding.

308
00:15:33,750 --> 00:15:37,833
Koito only shot me
with a Type 26 revolver.

309
00:15:37,916 --> 00:15:39,541
If you shoot that gun
at a pig's nose

310
00:15:39,625 --> 00:15:40,833
it'll just bounce off.

311
00:15:40,916 --> 00:15:42,375
It's incredibly weak.

312
00:15:42,458 --> 00:15:45,166
Nobody could kill me
with something like that.

313
00:15:45,250 --> 00:15:48,166
But Suzukawa was weaker
than a pig's nose.

314
00:15:48,250 --> 00:15:49,791
[gasps]

315
00:15:49,875 --> 00:15:52,125
Did Suzukawa not make it?

316
00:16:00,958 --> 00:16:02,416
Ah!

317
00:16:02,500 --> 00:16:04,791
♪

318
00:16:04,875 --> 00:16:06,666
[gasps]
They found us.

319
00:16:06,750 --> 00:16:08,041
-[ALL gasp]
-Hurry!

320
00:16:08,125 --> 00:16:09,833
We need to cross
the Daisetsuzan.

321
00:16:11,791 --> 00:16:15,000
Are you being serious?
These mountains are huge!

322
00:16:20,750 --> 00:16:22,583
[wind gushing]

323
00:16:23,708 --> 00:16:24,916
What do we do?

324
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:26,958
The weather just changed
so quickly.

325
00:16:27,041 --> 00:16:28,583
Why is this wind so cold?

326
00:16:28,666 --> 00:16:30,500
It'll only get stronger.

327
00:16:30,583 --> 00:16:31,625
And it'll rain, too.

328
00:16:31,708 --> 00:16:33,166
We have to go back!

329
00:16:33,250 --> 00:16:35,500
Don't be stupid.
They're still following us.

330
00:16:35,583 --> 00:16:37,750
[SHIRAISHI] Do we dig a hole
in the snow and hide?

331
00:16:37,833 --> 00:16:40,458
[ASIRPA] No. There's not enough
snow left to do it.

332
00:16:40,541 --> 00:16:42,458
[SHIRAISHI exhales]

333
00:16:42,541 --> 00:16:43,916
[laughs]

334
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:45,875
Shiraishi's acting strange.

335
00:16:45,958 --> 00:16:48,208
Look for a place
to hide from the wind.

336
00:16:48,291 --> 00:16:49,916
Or you'll die of hypothermia.

337
00:16:51,208 --> 00:16:54,083
Yuk. Sugimoto.
Shoot the bucks.

338
00:16:54,166 --> 00:16:56,250
We're gonna need
three of the big ones.

339
00:16:56,333 --> 00:16:57,583
You want me to shoot the deer?

340
00:16:57,666 --> 00:16:58,791
♪

341
00:17:01,083 --> 00:17:02,666
Two at the same time?

342
00:17:02,750 --> 00:17:04,000
[gunshot]

343
00:17:04,083 --> 00:17:05,875
Hurry and skin them fast!

344
00:17:05,958 --> 00:17:07,291
Don't worry how well.

345
00:17:07,375 --> 00:17:09,416
We're gonna hide
inside the deer's bodies.

346
00:17:09,500 --> 00:17:11,250
We're crawling
inside corpses?

347
00:17:11,333 --> 00:17:12,791
[SHIRAISHI laughing]

348
00:17:17,708 --> 00:17:19,625
Pawci Kamuy got him good.

349
00:17:19,708 --> 00:17:21,083
He's gone batty.

350
00:17:21,166 --> 00:17:22,666
-Shiraish--
-Stand still!

351
00:17:22,750 --> 00:17:24,541
You can't run with that wound.

352
00:17:24,625 --> 00:17:26,833
You and Ogata need
to skin the deer.

353
00:17:31,875 --> 00:17:33,750
[SUGIMOTO]
Shiraishi?

354
00:17:33,833 --> 00:17:35,166
[gasps]

355
00:17:35,250 --> 00:17:36,541
But Asirpa's still...

356
00:17:39,125 --> 00:17:40,541
-[grunting]
-Hey, Sugimoto!

357
00:17:43,458 --> 00:17:45,833
You're so pretty and soft
and warm and...

358
00:17:45,916 --> 00:17:48,083
♪

359
00:17:51,208 --> 00:17:52,958
Asirpa!

360
00:17:53,041 --> 00:17:55,250
Hey, Asirpa!

361
00:17:58,250 --> 00:18:00,250
Come on, where are you?

362
00:18:00,333 --> 00:18:02,625
[ASIRPA]
Sugimoto!

363
00:18:02,708 --> 00:18:03,666
[gasps]

364
00:18:03,750 --> 00:18:05,791
[ASIRPA]
Sugimoto!

365
00:18:05,875 --> 00:18:07,500
♪

366
00:18:08,583 --> 00:18:10,000
[BOTH panting]

367
00:18:11,666 --> 00:18:13,083
I lost Shiraishi.

368
00:18:13,166 --> 00:18:15,000
No, he came back.

369
00:18:15,083 --> 00:18:16,708
Huh? Oh, thank goodness.

370
00:18:16,791 --> 00:18:20,083
Listen, are you okay?
You look pale.

371
00:18:20,166 --> 00:18:22,375
Yes, I'm fine. What about you?

372
00:18:22,458 --> 00:18:23,500
We need to head back.

373
00:18:23,583 --> 00:18:26,000
♪

374
00:18:31,750 --> 00:18:33,083
Sugimoto!

375
00:18:43,541 --> 00:18:44,708
Why didn't you shoot?

376
00:18:48,083 --> 00:18:49,500
This deer is me.

377
00:18:49,583 --> 00:18:51,750
♪

378
00:18:55,041 --> 00:18:56,708
[gunshot]

379
00:19:01,541 --> 00:19:02,458
[exhales]

380
00:19:13,541 --> 00:19:15,458
Is your wound bothering you?

381
00:19:15,541 --> 00:19:17,541
No. I'm okay.

382
00:19:17,625 --> 00:19:19,916
It's gonna be better
by tomorrow morning.

383
00:19:21,458 --> 00:19:24,791
Suzukawa. Did he suffer?

384
00:19:24,875 --> 00:19:25,875
How did he die?

385
00:19:28,125 --> 00:19:31,500
Asirpa, Suzukawa was a bad man.

386
00:19:31,583 --> 00:19:34,125
Bad men don't have human hearts.

387
00:19:34,208 --> 00:19:37,291
So they feel less pain
than normal people.

388
00:19:37,375 --> 00:19:39,333
You don't need to
feel sorry for them.

389
00:19:39,416 --> 00:19:41,791
Are you making fun of me
because I'm a kid?

390
00:19:41,875 --> 00:19:43,750
Don't try to feed me
that stuff.

391
00:19:43,833 --> 00:19:46,541
No, it's what
I've tried to think.

392
00:19:46,625 --> 00:19:48,291
During the war,

393
00:19:48,375 --> 00:19:50,875
I would say that
the enemies weren't like us.

394
00:19:50,958 --> 00:19:53,375
That they didn't
suffer as they died.

395
00:19:53,458 --> 00:19:55,708
On the battlefield
your old self dies.

396
00:19:55,791 --> 00:19:58,458
You become someone else
in order to keep fighting.

397
00:20:01,458 --> 00:20:03,583
-[shouting]
-[groaning]

398
00:20:04,958 --> 00:20:05,958
[explosion]

399
00:20:09,333 --> 00:20:11,125
[panting]

400
00:20:11,208 --> 00:20:12,916
[screaming]

401
00:20:15,041 --> 00:20:17,333
[SUGIMOTO] Destroying the person
you once were,

402
00:20:17,416 --> 00:20:19,125
is the only way to survive.

403
00:20:22,500 --> 00:20:26,250
But then, could anybody
go back to who they were?

404
00:20:26,333 --> 00:20:30,666
I have no doubt some people did.
They went back home.

405
00:20:30,750 --> 00:20:32,666
Maybe they were able
to get their old selves back

406
00:20:32,750 --> 00:20:35,458
spending time
with their families.

407
00:20:35,541 --> 00:20:37,250
But those who couldn't
return to themselves

408
00:20:37,333 --> 00:20:39,083
after coming back to Japan,

409
00:20:40,458 --> 00:20:42,666
their hearts are still
on the battlefield.

410
00:20:44,833 --> 00:20:46,250
[ASIRPA chomping]

411
00:20:46,333 --> 00:20:47,250
[SUGIMOTO]
Hmm?

412
00:20:47,333 --> 00:20:50,541
Asirpa. what are you eating?

413
00:20:50,625 --> 00:20:52,291
It's deer liver.

414
00:20:52,375 --> 00:20:53,875
You should have some, too.

415
00:20:53,958 --> 00:20:55,875
You lost a lot of blood today.

416
00:20:55,958 --> 00:20:57,458
I really wanna eat
the brains, too,

417
00:20:57,541 --> 00:21:00,208
but we'll have to wait
till the wind stops.

418
00:21:00,291 --> 00:21:03,458
You really appreciate
a good brain, don't you, Asirpa?

419
00:21:03,541 --> 00:21:06,458
You know I do.
What you do love besides osoma?

420
00:21:06,541 --> 00:21:07,916
You mean food?

421
00:21:09,333 --> 00:21:11,291
Dried persimmons, I guess.

422
00:21:11,375 --> 00:21:13,041
What is that?

423
00:21:13,125 --> 00:21:17,291
That's right, there aren't
any persimmon trees in Hokkaido.

424
00:21:18,625 --> 00:21:21,625
You just take bitter persimmons
and dry them out.

425
00:21:21,708 --> 00:21:23,958
After you dry 'em,
they become sweet.

426
00:21:24,958 --> 00:21:27,625
I haven't had one
for several years.

427
00:21:27,708 --> 00:21:30,125
Before I left for the war,

428
00:21:30,208 --> 00:21:31,833
that was the last time.

429
00:21:32,958 --> 00:21:34,916
Why didn't you have one
when you finally got back

430
00:21:35,000 --> 00:21:36,125
from the fighting?

431
00:21:37,708 --> 00:21:39,625
It was spring.
There weren't any.

432
00:21:41,416 --> 00:21:42,625
[ASIRPA]
I see.

433
00:21:43,625 --> 00:21:46,916
Do you think maybe
if you eat dried persimmons,

434
00:21:47,000 --> 00:21:48,916
you might go back to being
the same person

435
00:21:49,000 --> 00:21:50,500
you were before the war?

436
00:21:50,583 --> 00:21:53,041
♪

437
00:21:53,125 --> 00:21:54,750
[sniffles quietly]

438
00:21:54,833 --> 00:21:56,875
♪

439
00:22:10,791 --> 00:22:12,541
Once all of this is over,

440
00:22:13,500 --> 00:22:15,875
you'll have to take me
to your homeland with you.

441
00:22:18,916 --> 00:22:20,208
That's all I want.

442
00:22:20,291 --> 00:22:22,541
Just to try
some dried persimmons.

443
00:22:24,541 --> 00:22:26,666
That a deal?

444
00:22:26,750 --> 00:22:28,041
Sugimoto?

445
00:24:06,708 --> 00:24:10,041
[NARRATOR]
Next Time, "Ani Nekko."

